page.title: 01Hockley Woods
page.content: Hockley woods has many different trees mammals and birds in it. Hornbeam is the most numerous tree in Hockley Woods but you can aso see oak, ash, silver birch and elm. Holly and Hawthorn grow quite abundantly in bushes. Grey squirrels are common running about collecting nuts.Foxes and badgers may be seen as well as hedgehogs,rabbits and mole hills.It is peaceful in the woods. All you can hear is birds singing in and around the woods.Pigeons and magpies are the commonest birds, but woodpeckers and jays, robins, nuthatches, and treecreepers can be seen.There are ponds with newts, toads and frogs.Some ofthe trees have been coppiced (cut at the bottom of the trunk) to let in the light and let other plants grow.On the paths there are faggots (wood chips) which stop you getting muddy.
